\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this note is to study the roles of transfers and debt as tools to hedge aggregate shocks in presence of incomplete markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with the representative agent model studied in AMSS and make two changes: first, the government trades a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bond and second, the government is prohibited from using transfers. The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

risky
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bond is a security whose payoffs 
\begin_inset Formula $P_t(s^t)$
\end_inset

 are correlated with the aggregate shocks. This feature allows us to vary the government's ability to span aggregate shocks while keeping markets incomplete. Below we will characterize two polar cases analytically: a) risk-free bond where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_t(s^t)=1$
\end_inset

 and b) perfect spanning where 
\begin_inset Formula $\corr(P_t,g_t)=\pm 1$
\end_inset

. Lastly we develop an approximation result for intermediate cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main finding is that the levels and fluctuations in tax rates and government debt are both driven by the covariance between payoff on the bonds and the exogenous needs for revenue driven by exogenous government purchases. With perfect spanning, the joint distribution of long-run debt and taxes is degenerate, taxes and debt both diverge in an economy with only a risk-free bond being traded. The approximation result allows us to estimate the rates of convergence and volatility of debt and taxes for intermediate cases.
