LatexCommand ref
reference "lem-convergence mu"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_t$
\end_inset

 converge to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^*$
\end_inset

 respectively. Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq-foc c_2 QLRA"

\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^*\geq \omega$
\end_inset

. This provides us with another bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*$
\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula \[\mu^*\leq  \min \left \{\frac{\omega }{(1+\gamma)},(1-n)\omega \right\}\]
\end_inset

. We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*= \min\{(1-n)\omega,\frac{\omega}{1+\gamma}\}$
\end_inset

. Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*$
\end_inset

 is strictly lower than the bound. Then we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2,t}$
\end_inset

 converges to a finite positive number 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2^*$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_tc_{1,t}=\frac{n\theta l^*-g(s_t)-(1-n)c_2^*}{n}$
\end_inset

.The implementability constraint 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq-implementability constraint"

\end_inset

 further implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_tb_t$
\end_inset

 has to diverge. Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_tb_t=\infty$
\end_inset

, this yields a contradiction as the maximum revenue the government can collect is finite in this economy. On the other hand if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_tb_t=-\infty$
\end_inset

, we will violate the productive agent's natural debt limit. This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^*>-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^*<\infty$
\end_inset

 and hence his post tax income is bounded. 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Since we do not impose non-negativity constraint on his consumption, in prnciple he could sustain arbitrary debt with arbitrary negative consumption, but under the current guess 
\begin_inset Formula $\min{c_t}>-\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we have two cases to consider for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*$
\end_inset

. Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*=(1-n)\omega$
\end_inset

. This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^*=\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2^*=\infty$
\end_inset

. This makes limiting transfers,
\begin_inset Formula $T^*$
\end_inset

 diverge to infinity and we can construct a solution where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_tb_t=-\infty$
\end_inset

. However tax rates will be bounded and given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[\tau^*=\frac{-\gamma (1-n)}{1-(1+\gamma)(1+n)}\]
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed


\begin_layout Standard
Under this solution 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1,t}$
\end_inset

 diverges to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 and we do not violate any natural debt limits for the productive agent.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^*=\frac{\omega}{1+\gamma}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^*\to -\infty$
\end_inset

. In this case, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_2^*$
\end_inset

 finite and again the government debt 
\begin_inset Formula $b_t$
\end_inset

 diverges to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

. The transfers are given by the following expression, 
\begin_inset Formula \[T^*=\left(\frac{\omega(1-n)-\frac{\omega}{1+\gamma}}{n(1-\omega)}\right)^{-\frac{1}{\sigma}}\]
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which of this case characterizes the solution depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\gamma}{1+\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

. As 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to 0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\omega}{1+\gamma}<\omega$
\end_inset

 and conversely when 
\begin_inset Formula $n \to 1$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(1-n)<\frac{\omega}{1+\gamma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

